02:29:54,121 --> 02:30:00,366
Whereas the mayor and city administration recently announced the receipt of a $200,000 grant for Medford zero waste initiative.

1637
02:30:00,646 --> 02:30:09,172
And whereas as part of this initiative, the mayor announced that her administration would reduce tax collection, trash collection to once every two weeks, starting in July, 2027.

1638
02:30:09,212 --> 02:30:16,478
And whereas the city council supports efforts to reduce waste increases to free weekly composting and limit cost growth of waste collection.

1639
02:30:17,178 --> 02:30:37,711
that has hurt our city budget and whereas residents have very significant concerns about the impact of reducing trash collection to once every two weeks for residents and the need for greater efforts by the mayor to inform and engage residents regarding our solid waste collection program changes now therefore be it resolved by the medford city council that the mayor and city administration provide a report to the council and residents explaining the changes

1640
02:30:38,371 --> 02:30:40,812
they are making to the city's waste collection program.

1641
02:30:41,292 --> 02:30:48,134
Be it for the resolve that the mayor, city administration share all resources that they are making available to residents to reduce any negative impacts of these changes.

1642
02:30:48,614 --> 02:30:56,597
Be it for the resolve that the mayor and city administration hold a public forum to hear from residents about their concerns and explore potential alternative options to move the city towards zero waste goals.

1643
02:30:57,177 --> 02:31:02,399
Be it for the resolve that the city council appreciates the work of our DPW commissioner and planning development and sustainability director.

1644
02:31:02,899 --> 02:31:17,754
The council requests that the mayor provide additional resources for our dedicated city staff so they have the capacity to effectively communicate with residents regarding the proposed timeline and reasoning for these changes, explore the benefits and costs of alternative timelines and plans, and outline a mitigation strategy to address any negative impacts.

1645
02:31:17,914 --> 02:31:18,655
Councilor Callahan.

1646
02:31:22,342 --> 02:31:22,642
Thank you.

1647
02:31:24,024 --> 02:31:36,177
I think we, certainly I, I'll speak for myself, I do understand the purpose of this change.

1648
02:31:36,357 --> 02:31:41,042
I know that the waste collection costs have been going up.

1649
02:31:41,803 --> 02:31:43,725
a lot.

1650
02:31:43,745 --> 02:31:56,498
And also just in terms of climate change, wanting to be a sustainable city, moving toward more composting and offering our composting for free, and that hopefully that will naturally reduce the amount of trash.

1651
02:31:57,199 --> 02:31:58,900
These are laudable goals.

1652
02:32:00,121 --> 02:32:01,503
The problem is that

1653
02:32:03,283 --> 02:32:18,529
This was brought up in like the 11th paragraph of a statement about composting and people are getting this and realizing suddenly that a service that they depend upon is about to be cut in half.

1654
02:32:20,311 --> 02:32:33,671
It's really important to me that when we have climate goals that those climate goals are something that the residents of our city understand the residents of our city can get behind that we not have climate goals be something negative that people.

1655
02:32:34,732 --> 02:32:37,733
dislike and see as a bad thing.

1656
02:32:38,913 --> 02:32:52,297
So really all we're asking for is for this, the rollout to be done right, to make sure that we meet our residents' needs, that we offer any alternatives if necessary for the things that people come up with.

1657
02:32:53,237 --> 02:32:59,419
So we really just want to make sure that this rollout is done the right way and that our residents are fully informed.

1658
02:32:59,439 --> 02:32:59,879
Thank you.

1659
02:33:01,700 --> 02:33:02,740
Thank you, Councilor Callahan.

1660
02:33:04,168 --> 02:33:22,623
You know, I maybe see it a little bit differently, although we are co-sponsors of this resolution, I just, the city is not ready for a change of this magnitude and the way that it was announced was at the best burying the lead and at worst, deeply confusing and worrying.

1661
02:33:25,677 --> 02:33:30,980
I also understand, right, maybe some of the motivations here outside of health insurance and pension costs.

1662
02:33:31,040 --> 02:33:34,581
One of the things that is cost going up the fastest is our waste removal contract.

1663
02:33:35,162 --> 02:33:43,946
The flip side of that is that the one thing that every resident in the way they interact with the city every week is trash and recycling and compost.

1664
02:33:44,466 --> 02:33:51,289
It's the one thing that the city does for any resident in a one, two, three family home every week.

1665
02:33:52,095 --> 02:34:02,644
And I think the idea of essentially announcing to the city that that's going to change in paragraph 10 of a press release that says we just got a big grant, not even a big grant.

1666
02:34:02,664 --> 02:34:08,228
We just got a $200,000 grant and it's a $220 million city budget is not the way to do this.

1667
02:34:08,989 --> 02:34:17,936
Even if I 100% understand the intent and agree with the goals, you know, we had a conversation with the administration two years ago,

1668
02:34:18,799 --> 02:34:39,994
that said we're moving to a new waste contract, we're bringing in free composting, there's going to be a bunch of benchmarks and checks along the way, and at some point we're going to come back to you and say, we think we've done enough education of the public, we think that we have enough uptake on the composting program, we're seeing changes in the way that people are putting their trash out.

1669
02:34:40,634 --> 02:34:50,724
And that that was going to then inform a process where you go out to residents and say, hey, we've done a lot together over the past few years around changing our waste stream.

1670
02:34:51,405 --> 02:35:01,415
And we think that we now have met some conditions and there's enough time for us to have a conversation about making a change to trash.

1671
02:35:03,177 --> 02:35:04,138
But this is not that.

1672
02:35:05,547 --> 02:35:09,249
that groundwork laying, I have not seen it.

1673
02:35:09,289 --> 02:35:17,832
We have not had a bunch of meetings in this body or we have not seen a bunch of public meetings and public forums hosted by the city saying, here's the update on the composting program.

1674
02:35:18,293 --> 02:35:22,815
We're actually seeing that the trash, you know, our trash weight is going down, the bins are less full.

1675
02:35:23,175 --> 02:35:28,177
We're not seeing any of the benchmarks that would lead us to believe that this is a good change.

1676
02:35:29,337 --> 02:35:34,460
And I think to have not laid that groundwork and then for us to, you know,

1677
02:35:35,560 --> 02:35:53,489
The fact that this was not the lead of the press release, that the press release wasn't titled City Planning to Move to Every Other Week Trash Removal in 2027, and then saying at least some of the stuff that we were told we were going to hear, I think has rubbed a lot of people the wrong way.

1678
02:35:53,509 --> 02:35:55,150
I think it set up

1679
02:35:55,850 --> 02:35:59,551
quite frankly, this program for failure, because I think there's not trust in it.

1680
02:36:00,832 --> 02:36:10,536
And I think it's a yet another example where the resources for communication have not been provided to the people who are tasked with communicating about major changes.

1681
02:36:12,376 --> 02:36:14,697
I heard that message loud and clear six months ago about zoning.

1682
02:36:15,378 --> 02:36:16,138
